In addition to these host immune responses that are directly or indirectly triggered by the Zn, the same element also acts directly on the infectious pathogens more specifically for a number of viruses. 
 In vitro studies suggested that intracellular Zn
 2+ inhibit the replicative cycle of a number of viruses including influenza virus (
 Uchide et al., 2002), respiratory syncytial virus (
 Suara and Crowe, 2004), and several picornaviruses (
 Korant et al., 1974; 
 Krenn et al., 2009; 
 Lanke et al., 2007). More particularly, Zn
 2+ was shown to inhibit polyprotein processing in cells infected with human rhinovirus and coxsackievirus B3 (
 Krenn et al., 2009). Replication of other viruses such as HIV, HSV, and vaccinia virus as well as SARS-CoVs were also known to be inhibited by Zn salts. In those viruses, Zn is known to inhibit the viral entry, blocking of polyprotein processing, or inhibition of viral RdRp activity (
 Haraguchi et al., 1999; 
 Katz and Margalith, 1981; 
 Kaushik et al., 2017; 
 te Velthuis et al., 2010).
